<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_4:_3.2_Cross-Price_Elasticity_of_Demand">Notes for Week 4: 3.2 Cross-Price Elasticity of Demand</span></h2>
<p>Cross-price elasticity of demand=&#160;% change of quantity of product X demanded /&#160;% change in price of related product Y
- $$\epsilon&#95;x = \cfrac{\% change Q&#95;x}{\% change P&#95;y} = \cfrac{\% \Delta Q&#95;x}{\% \Delta P&#95;y}$$ <br /></p>
<ul>
<li>For products that are complements, E. is negative: if price of a complement Y goes up, consumed quantity of good X decreases.

<ul>
<li>Example: pizza and beer are complements.  </li>
<li>y = pizza</li>
<li>x = beer</li>
<li>So if the price of pizza goes up (say 10%), then $$\Delta P&#95;y = 10 \%$$ <br /></li>
<li>Since pizza is a complement of beer,demand for beer goes down when price of pizza goes up, so $$Q&#95;x = -10 \%$$ <br /></li>
<li>Therefore, the cross-price elasticity, $$\cfrac{\% \Delta Q&#95;x}{\% \Delta P&#95;y}$$, is negative</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><br />
<ul><li> For products that are substitutes, E. is positive: if price of substitute Y goes up, demanded quantity if good X increases.</p>
</li></ul>


